<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-hplwgP-d8f1tMhq0K0gykg" name="new_guideline,_iPfsIJauEeCPtY0LnWkRDw" guid="-hplwgP-d8f1tMhq0K0gykg" changeDate="2012-09-28T13:24:03.658-0700" version="7.5.1">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot;>&#xD;
    The method of ASIL tailoring during the design process given in ISO 26262 is called &quot;ASIL decomposition&quot;. During the&#xD;
    allocation process, benefit can be obtained from architectural decisions and the existence of independent architectural&#xD;
    elements. This offers the opportunity to do the following:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        implement safety requirements redundantly by these independent architectural elements&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        assign a potentially lower ASIL to these redundant safety requirements.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If there is no independence between the elements, the ASIL of the safety goal is inherited by each requirement and&#xD;
    element.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Inputs&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The inputs to the ASIL decomposition stage is dependent upon the stage of development.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In terms of safety requirements at the applied system, hardware or software level&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In terms of the architectural information at the applied system, hardware or software level&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    ASIL decomposition can also be applied at the Concept phases in which case the item definition and safety goals can&#xD;
    also provide input.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The diagram below provides the general pattern for ASIL decomposition. It is advised that users refer to ISO 26262,&#xD;
    Volume 9, Clause 5 for detailed requirements and guidance on ASIL decomposition.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;resources/ASIL%20decomp.png&quot; width=&quot;488&quot; height=&quot;351&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Work products&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Work products are updated depending upon the stage of development applied and also the ASIL attribute of the&#xD;
    affected&amp;nbsp;safety requirements and elements.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br /></mainDescription>
